23.6	We recommended that the Municipal Government:
formulate its APP based on the different programs, activities and projects that are crucial to the effective discharge of its governmental function or are in pursuit of its principal mandate;
ensure that all procurement of supplies and other goods needed for the day-to-day operations of the municipality shall be undertaken in accordance with the approved APP to obtain the most advantageous price;
consider whenever justified by the conditions, resort to any of the alternative methods of procurement; and
shall ensure that the most advantageous price for the Government is obtained.

We recommended that Management require the:
Inventory Committee to continue and further intensify their efforts to complete the conduct of physical inventory of Property, Plant, and Equipment (PPE) and Investment Property, including a reconciliation of the physical count with the property and accounting records, as required by Chapter 4 of the Handbook on Property and Supply Management System and Paragraph 4 of Section 114 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I. Any discrepancies should be thoroughly investigated, cleared, immediately reconciled, and supported with written explanations from accountable persons, if necessary;
City Accounting Office and City General Services Office to enhance further their documentation and record-keeping practices related to PPE and Investment Property by preparing and continuously maintaining and updating PPE ledger cards and property cards, respectively. Both offices should ensure that all movements of PPE are properly recorded and documented to facilitate accurate reconciliation and reporting;
The Disposal Committee to facilitate immediate disposal of the unserviceable properties in accordance with COA and Department of Budget and Management (DBM) Joint Circular No. 2024-1 or the Revised Manual on the Disposal of Government Properties; and
Relevant members of the Inventory Committee and Disposal Committee to undergo training on proper inventory procedures, reconciliation processes and record-keeping practices, as well as disposal procedures, including appraisal, documentation, and methods of disposal, if necessary.

We recommended that Management require:
The creation of an inventory committee consisting of representatives from different concerned offices to conduct an inventory of the local roads under the jurisdiction of the city who will prepare the necessary Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System (RPCRNS) using the form in Annex C of COA Circular 2015-008 dated November 25, 2015. The RPCRNS should be reconciled with the Accounting and GSO records;
The City Engineer to provide the City Accountant and the City General Services Officer with the complete description and segregation of road components for those with data on construction costs. For those not posted in the registry but without identified cost and those included in the RPCRNS but not in the registry, the fair value must be used in determining the cost of road components and thereafter shall provide the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;
The City Accountant to depreciate the carrying amount of existing roads and its components to reflect the asset in its used condition and accordingly adjust the amount recorded in the Road Network account supported by the RPCRNS, Registry Infrastructure for Roads and working paper on the determination of the depreciated replacement cost per registry. Subsequently, at the end of each year, a lapsing schedule for the computation of depreciation for each depreciable road component must be prepared as basis for recording depreciation expenses and the required Local Road Network Ledger Card for each road network shall likewise be maintained; and
The City General Services Office at the end or every accounting period to render a Report on Local Road Network using the pro-forma schedule in Annex A of same Circular and maintain local road inventory, Road Map and complete Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components.

To ensure fair presentation of the financial statements and compliance with accounting standards and regulations, we recommended that the City Accountant:
Conduct a thorough reconciliation of the Due from Other Funds and Due to Other Funds accounts to determine the cause of the discrepancy and make necessary adjustments to ensure that both accounts are properly recognized;
Prepare the necessary adjusting entries to correct the account balances;
Maintain subsidiary ledgers as necessary and include disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements for transparency; and
Strengthen internal controls and monitoring mechanisms to prevent future discrepancies in reciprocal accounts.

We recommended that Management:
Enhance the implementation of Social Services Projects to ensure balanced development across all sectors;
Ensure that all projects under the 20% Development Fund are well-planned and procurement-and-implementation-ready, in accordance with Item 3.2 of DBM-DOF-DILG JMC No. 1, s. 2020;
Reassess the viability of the Landbanking for City Government Development Projects, which have remained unimplemented for 9-10 years. If deemed impractical or non-priority, consider realignment or reprogramming of these funds for other eligible projects; and
Conduct a review of PPAs with remaining balances from prior years (₱9.470 million) and evaluate the feasibility of reprogramming them for other priority projects.

We recommended that Management:
Ensure efficient and effective implementation of all programmed projects identified during the budget year to optimize the utilization of the fund and to assure that the goals and objectives of reducing disaster risk and enhancing disaster preparedness and response capabilities are achieved;
To promptly complete the remaining unfinished projects under continuing appropriations and the special trust fund of the LDRRMF;
Ensure the allocation and utilization of LDRRMF according to the policies and guidelines primarily embodied in NDRRMC-DBM-DILG Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-1 dated March 25, 2013; and
Continuously comply with pertinent laws, rules and regulations in the recording, utilization and reporting of LDRRMF.

We recommended that Management:
Develop and enforce an internal memorandum or directive requiring all concerned personnel to submit the Acceptance and Inspection Reports (AIRs) within 24 hours of goods acceptance;
Implement a tracking system for AIR submission;
Assign a focal person responsible for consolidating and submitting AIRs to the Office of the Auditor within the prescribed timeframe; and
If necessary, conduct a re-orientation for General Services Office personnel and end-users regarding proper documentation and timely submission of AIRs in accordance with COA Circulars.

We recommended that the Local School Board, being the one responsible for the formulation, approval, and utilization of the SEF Budget as provided under RA No. 7160 or the Local Government Code:
Sustain its efforts in ensuring that all budgeted projects, programs, and activities are optimally and fully implemented within the target period and amount;
From time to time, revisit the revised guidelines on the use of SEF under DepEd-DBM-DILG Joint Circular No. 1, s. 2017 to ensure a more strategic and efficient formulation and utilization of resources for priority programs and projects;
Ensure that the allocation of the budget takes into account the priority areas specified under Section 100(c) of R.A. No. 7160; and
For the purpose of hiring teachers chargeable against the SEF, the LSB in each province, city or municipality should utilize the list found in the Registry of Qualified Applicants (RQA).
We further recommended that the City Budget Office provide the different schools, through their District Supervisors, information as to their available appropriations for prompt implementation. In turn, the different schools should maintain a registry of appropriations, obligations, and balances to have updated information that will facilitate their disbursement of funds.

Create an Inventory Committee to undertake the physical count of inventory items as of June 30 and December 31 of each year; prepare the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) by inventory account name and distribute the same as prescribed; to reconcile said report with the records of the City Accounting Office in accordance with Section 124, Volume I of MNGAS; and to submit to the Office of the Auditor the duplicate copy of the RPCI not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively;

Direct the City Accountant to correct the errors in recording purchases and 

issuances of inventories and observe the Perpetual Inventory System as method of recording inventories as prescribed under Section 51, Volume I of the MNGAS for LGUs; 

Instruct the City General Services Officer (GSO) and the City Accountant to maintain updated Stock Cards and Supplies Ledger Cards and regularly reconcile records to detect discrepancies and effect immediate corrections; and for the GSO to promptly prepare and submit the monthly SSMIs to the City Accountant for recording in compliance with Sections 119 and 120, Volume I, of the MNGAS for LGUs and strictly enjoin compliance with the above-cited rules for the fair presentation of inventory and 

related expense accounts in the financial statements.

City Accountant to prepare and maintain Local Road Network Ledger Cards for the road and its components namely: (1) road lot, (2) road pavement, (3) drainage and slope protection structures and (4) other miscellaneous structure.  Further, prepare a lapsing schedule for the computation of depreciation of each road component, and disclose the Road Network System in the Notes to Financial Statements;

City GSO to prepare and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network, maintain a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components, and maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map; and

City Accountant and the City GSO to secure from the City Engineer the complete description and cost segregation of road components of every road project undertaken for them to have a basis in recording the road networks in the Local Road Network Ledger Card and Local Road Network Property Card, respectively.

We recommended the Management to:
inform the Auditor in writing on the posting of infrastructure projects billboards within ten days after the award of the contract;
comply with the submission of monthly report of on-going and completed contracts.

We recommended that the Municipal Government:
formulate its APP based on the different programs, activities and projects that are crucial to the effective discharge of its governmental function or are in pursuit of its principal mandate;
ensure that all procurement of supplies and other goods needed for the day-to-day operations of the municipality shall be undertaken in accordance with the approved APP to obtain the most advantageous price;
consider whenever justified by the conditions, resort to any of the alternative methods of procurement; and
shall ensure that the most advantageous price for the Government is obtained.

We recommended that the City Mayor instruct the:
Inventory Committee to undertake the physical count of inventory items as of June 30 and December 31 of each year; to prepare the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) by inventory account name and distribute the same as prescribed;  to reconcile said report with the records of the City Accounting Office in accordance with Section 124, Volume I of MNGAS; and to submit to the Office of the Auditor the duplicate copy of the RPCI not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively;
City Accountant to use moving average method as costing method for valuation of inventories as prescribed under Section 115, Chapter 7, Volume I of the MNGAS for LGUs;
CGSO and the City Accountant to maintain updated Stock Cards and Supplies Ledger Cards and regularly reconcile records to detect discrepancies and effect immediate corrections; and for the GSO to promptly prepare and submit the monthly SSMIs to the City Accountant for recording in compliance with Sections 119 and 120, Volume I, of the MNGAS for LGUs; and
City Accountant to strictly enjoin compliance with the above-cited rules for the fair presentation of inventory and related expense accounts in the financial statements.

3.9	We recommended the following:
The ICO-Municipal Accountant, the Budget Officer, and the LDRRM Officer reconcile their records as to appropriation, obligation, and disbursements and submit relevant transactions documents/ reports for further audit verification;
The Municipal Accountant make the necessary adjusting entries in the Trust Liability – DRRM account under Trust Fund books;
The Municipal Accountant include in the disclosure the prior year's unexpended balances in the Notes to Financial Statements the details on the receipt and utilization of LDRRMF of the Municipality using the required format as required under Item 5.1.16 of COA Circular 2012 -002.
Make sure that disclosures made for the unexpended balance for the MDRRMF must be in accordance to Item 5.1.16 of COA Circular 2012 – 002 and the balance must be equal to the Trust Liability – DRRM account in the Financial Statements.
Maintain a separate registry of Appropriations, Allotments, and Obligations (RAAO) for LDRRMF QRF, MOOE and CO to facilitate reconciliation of records with the budget office and maintain Subsidiary ledgers to facilitate the transfers of the agency’s unutilized DRRMF to the special trust fund by year of transfer, receipt of NDRRMF by transferring agency, DRRMF from other LGUs by LGU, and other sources by donor at the end of each year to present fairly the said accounts in the financial statements at year-end.

16.6	We reiterated our recommendation that the ICO – Municipal Accountant:
Reconcile the RPT/SET Receivables and Deferred RPT/SET, further, draw an adjusting entry to correct the deficiencies, and regularly maintain Subsidiary Ledgers to monitor the movements made to the accounts;
Ensure adherence to the provisions of Section 20, Volume I of the NGAS Manual for LGUs.

18.9	We recommended that the Management:
Avail of the one-time cleansing of dormant accounts by creating a task force to assist the ICO- Municipal Accountant in following the general guidelines and in preparing the required schedules for monitoring purposes as well as undertake the procedures for the proper disposition of dormant accounts as provided for under Items 6.0 and 7.0 of COA Circular 2023-008 dated August 17, 2023;
Direct the ICO- Municipal Accountant through the HoA with/through the ATL and/or SA, depending on the jurisdictional amount, to file a request for the approval of COA to write off/derecognize from the books the dormant accounts in compliance with Item 8.0 of the Circular within one (1) year from the effectivity of the Circular. The request shall be supported with the documents listed in Annex 8, provided with index tabs, for easy reference;
Prepare the Schedules of Dormant Accounts (SDA) quarterly to be submitted to the ATL/SA on or before the 15th day of the ensuing month and disclose comparative information in the Notes to Financial Statements relative to the dormant accounts pursuant to Item 10.0 of the Circular; and
Looking forward, ensure that receivables below ten years are properly monitored to ensure their prompt collection and accurate recording in the FS including the provision of an allowance for impairment on receivables with doubtful collectability.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to:

instruct the Municipal Treasurer and the Supply Officer who sign the inspection and acceptance portions of the IAR respectively that henceforth, fill out the IAR properly, indicate the exact unit of measure and complete specifications of items accepted and inspected therein;

require the Municipal Treasurer to submit the official receipts for the payments of registration fees and term dues to the League of Municipalities and bond premium to the Bureau of the Treasury in the total amount of ₱93,100.00.

require the OIC - Municipal Accountant and the Supply Officer to submit the PARs of movable non-expendable properties in the total amount of ₱1,523,000.00.

require the OIC - Municipal Accountant and the Supply Officer to submit the ICS of semi-expendable items with total cost of ₱1,202,700.00.

require the OIC - Municipal Accountant, the Municipal Agricultural Officer and the Municipal Social Welfare Officer to submit the list of recipients of goods distributed indicating among others the date of distribution, exact unit of measure and complete specifications of items distributed in the total amount of ₱12,357,413.25.

require the OIC - Municipal Accountant to ensure that Itinerary of Travel is attached to all cash advances for travel expenses and Estimates of Breakdown of Expenditures for cash advances for specific activities;

require the OIC - Municipal Accountant and the BAC to submit the lacking documents for the payments of BAC honoraria as presented in Annex A. 6;

require the OIC - Municipal Accountant and the Head of Office in-charge for the conduct of meetings or activities in which snacks and or meals are served to take pictures of the participants taking their snacks and meals and attach a Project Proposal or its equivalent showing among others the budget for meals/snacks duly signed by the one in charge for such activity, and

instruct the OIC - Municipal Accountant that henceforth, always observe the documentary requirements in the disbursement of funds as embodied in COA Circular 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012, thus payment will be made only to claims with complete documentation in order to ascertain the validity, propriety and reliability of the transactions and to avoid suspensions in audit.

To facilitate the conduct and completion of the RPCPPE and to ensure that the PPE balances reflected in the FS are fairly presented; we recommended and Management agreed to:

Revisit the Inventory Committee and assign a new head to take charge of the inventory taking activities in accordance with the approved PIP and fast track the preparation of the RPCPPE or if necessary, assign or designate additional personnel to aid the GSO and inventory committee;

Exert more efforts in keeping and maintaining the property records up to date and take note of the procedures in the conduct of inventory taking which includes cases when no information could be found in both accounting and property records as stated in Section 6 of the COA Circular whichever is applicable;

Looking forward, ensure that the guidelines and procedures in the conduct of physical count of PPE as provided for in COA Circular 2020-006 are strictly observed to facilitate the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances.

a. The OIC- Municipal Accountant, GSO-designate and the Inventory Committee comply with the following duties and responsibilities as prescribed under COA Circular No. 2015-008, which provides among others:

• OIC- Municipal Accountant – to prepare and maintain subsidiary ledger cards for Local Road Network; 

• Inventory Committee – to promptly conduct an inventory of the road network system and submit the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System;

• General Services Officer–designate – to maintain Local Road Inventory and Road Map, to keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card, and prepare the annual Report on the Physical Count of the Local Road Network.

The OIC- Municipal Accountant prepares the bank reconciliation statement as of Dec. 31, 2022 to serve as the basis for the bank reconciliation for CY 2023 and maintain the preparation and submission of the statement monthly;

The OIC- Municipal Accountant and the Treasurer reconcile the Cash in Bank account balances with the Treasurer’s cash books starting with the funds that have the same noted difference since the previous year; and

Looking forward, conduct quarterly reconciliation of such balances so that the adjustments made or errors detected either by the Treasury or Accounting Office will be adjusted and posted in their respective books.

Prioritize the assignment of competent personnel in the Accounting Office who will be assigned to update the subsidiary ledgers of the cash accounts as well as focus on the preparation of bank reconciliation statements of the Municipality and it’s composite barangays with all of its supporting documents to aid in the verification of the report;

Prepare a timetable of activities including the responsible persons who will take charge of the possible plan of actions of the LGU with the end purpose of facilitating the prompt preparation and submission of the Bank Reconciliation Reports;

Request for the installation of the e-NGAs and e-Budget system for prompt recording of Subsidiary Ledgers and General Ledgers; and

Thereafter, submit Bank Reconciliation Statement to COA for verification in accordance with COA Circular No. 96-011 and conduct quarterly reconciliation of cash balances so that the adjustments made or errors detected either by the Treasury or Accounting Office will be adjusted and posted in their respective books.

The Municipal Accountant prepare adjusting entries of affected accounts by debiting Due from LGUs and crediting Prior Years Adjustment;

The Punong Barangay submit fund utilization report of the project; and

For future implementations, the LGU shall prepare a Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) for every fund transferred to the Barangays and require its immediate liquidation in accordance with the MOA if the purpose for which it had been transferred had been served.

The Human Resource and Management Officer and the Agency Authorized Officer facilitate the update of any changes in the Municipality’s membership records promptly to ensure reconciliation of records with the GSIS and avoid the occurrence of delinquent premium contributions;

The employees/personnel listed with delinquent loan repayments coordinate with the GSIS for the reconciliation of their loan accounts. Furthermore, require the OIC- Municipal Accountant to monitor the compliance of the concerned personnel with delinquent loan repayments; and

Looking forward, concerned employees continue their payments to the GSIS thru over the counter in case they have availed any GSIS loans from their previous employers to avoid incurrence of interests and surcharges of their GSIS loan accounts.

The OIC-Municipal Accountant submits a justification for why the grant of honoraria to BAC Members, BAC Secretariat, and TWG was not subjected to withholding tax;

The OIC-Municipal Accountant includes the total honoraria received in its computation of the income tax of those employees’ part of BAC Members, BAC Secretariat, and TWG; and

The Municipal Accountant ensures that withholding taxes are deducted from the payment of honoraria of BAC Members, BAC Secretariat, and TWG in accordance with BIR Revenue Memorandum Order No. 23-2014 dated June 20, 2014.

We recommended that the Management: 

Provide justifications citing the causes of non-compliance and install mechanisms to address the reasons for the non-compliance with RA 9184;

Furnish this Office a copy of the Executive Legislative Agenda together with the related reports for reference in audit;

Instruct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to always conduct the bidding process prior to the execution of the activity according to the provisions cited in RA 9184; and

Ensure strict adherence to the provisions of the procurement process stated in RA 9184 to guarantee the competitiveness, validity and timeliness of the procurement.

We recommended that the Management:

Prepare and submit the Annual Procurement Plan – Common Use Supplies and Equipment (APP-CSE) for 2024 to the Procurement Service of the Department of Budget and Management (PS-DBM) via the Virtual Store (VS) within the prescribed period this year;

Require each department/ end-user unit to carefully plan and monitor the procurement of common use supplies through proper forecasting, projections, and estimations of inventories to be used and stocked and accomplish the PPMP template before submitting the same to the Budget Officer for Budget approval and BAC Secretariat for consolidation;

Direct the Designated General Service Officer to coordinate with the BAC secretariat to get the consolidated and funded APP in order to make a detailed and thorough three-month forecast of the common-use supplies to be purchased by the Municipality in the PS-DBM;

After which procure the unavailable items from the PS-DBM comprising the three-month supplies from other suppliers using the RFQ in order to avail of advantageous bulk purchase prices and also to avoid price fluctuations of purchasing the same supplies from different suppliers;

Monitor the issuance of supplies to each department by using the Requisition Issue Slip and reporting the same to the Accounting Department monthly using the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued for the month together with the stock card as proof; and

Revisit the personnel complement in the GSO who will handle the procurement and maintenance of supplies, including the monitoring and reporting of its issuance.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:

Stop the practice of rendering overtime services and overtime pay to work activities which do not call for overtime as listed in Section 4 of CSC – DBM Joint Circular No. 1, series of 2015;

Thoroughly plan the Municipality’s work commitment deadlines to ensure that deadlines are meet without resorting to rendition of overtime services, unless the situations enumerated in Section 4 of the said circular are satisfied;

Strictly comply with the Section 4.1.7 of COA Circular 97-002 that a cash advance is used solely for its specific purpose;

Revisit Revenue Regulations No. 8-2018 dated January 25, 2018 to enhance the Municipality’s compliance with tax laws and avoid payment of penalties and surcharges in the future; and

Utilize the LGU’s vast manpower resources to its full potential by making certain that all employees are being productive during office hours.

We recommended that the Management:

Require the concerned accountable officers to refund the ₱71,730.50 excess claims;

Submit the noted lacking attachments in Annex O;

Claim only the lawful and allowable proportionate DTE in situations where the meals, transportation, and accommodations are already provided for by other parties;

Provide correcting entries to correctly recognize the refund of excess cash advance; and

Looking forward, firmly observe the provisions of Executive Order No. 77 in the claim of travel allowances and COA Circular No. 97-002 on the grant and liquidation of cash advances for travel.

Require the Municipal Planning and Development Officer to ensure that the PPAs to be included in the 20% Development Fund are compliant with the relevant guidelines on the said fund to minimize frequent realignment of funds;

Require the Municipal Budget Officer to maintain Registries to record the changes in the budget;

Looking forward, coordinate with the Local Finance Committee to improve the budget preparation process to come up with a more comprehensive budget to prioritize and put into action its plans, programs and policies within the constraints of its financial capability as dictated by economic conditions.

Revisit the personnel complement in the Municipal Treasurer’s Office to ensure continuous operation without affecting operational efficiency in cases where erring AOs will be sanctioned for continuous non-compliance;

Require the Municipal Treasurer to exercise proper management of the funds by:

• ensuring accurate and timely reporting and confirm that records in the cashbooks and in the Report of Collections and Deposits are reconciled each month;

• ensuring adequate bond for all AOs based on their actual total accountability in pursuance to Treasury Circular No. 02-2009 dated August 6, 2009;

•monitoring closely/regularly the activities of all collectors and ensure that all their activities are in accordance with existing rules and regulations; and

• requiring all AOs to strictly comply with the prompt deposit of all collections intact to avoid accumulation of cash in their possession; 

Require all AOs to explain and justify in cases of failure to follow the existing regulations for collections and deposits;

With close monitoring, strictly impose penalties and sanctions in case of non-compliance thereof especially for those who commits the same violations for three consecutive months by revisiting the existing local issuances and civil service law, rules and regulations; and

Direct the Designated Municipal Accountant to update the Subsidiary Ledgers especially for cash accounts as well as prepare the Bank Reconciliation Statements monthly for submission to the Office of the Auditor to facilitate the conduct of cash examination and for check and balance

a. Submit the said lacking documentary requirements as shown in the attached schedule (Annex B);

b. Require the concerned official to refund the total excess amount of ₱352,112.48;

c. Ensure that the itinerary of travel supporting travel claims shall be properly accomplished and duly approved, i.e., all details of the travel shall be included in the approved itinerary and detailed computation and breakdown of claims shall be accurately presented therein; and

d. Ensure strict compliance on the laws, rules and regulations on the claims for traveling expenses to avoid possible misuse of government funds.

We recommended that Management give justification on the aforementioned lapses.  Moreover, in order to correct the aforementioned deficiencies, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

instruct all the heads of offices to fill out all the data in the PR and indicate the exact unit of measure and complete specifications of items being requested to be purchased; 


instruct the Supply Officer to see to it that all the data in the RFQ/Canvass Paper are completely filled out and that the exact unit of measure and complete specifications of items being canvassed are indicated therein except the brand name;


instruct the Supply Officer to see to it that all data in the PO are completely filled out and the exact unit of measure and complete specifications of items being ordered are indicated therein including the brand name of the item if such was indicated by the winning bidder in the RFQ/Canvass Paper;

instruct the Municipal Treasurer and the Supply Officer who sign the inspection and acceptance portions of the AIR respectively that such document is properly filled out and the exact unit of measure and complete specifications of items accepted and inspected be indicated therein;

instruct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to see to it that all the data in the Abstract of Bids are completely filled out including the signatories indicated therein;

instruct the BAC Chairman, the BAC Technical Working Group (TWG) and the Municipal Accountant  to see to it that  the Notice of  Award is duly signed by the supplier/contractor and the Municipal Mayor;


require the heads of offices to see to it that the Itinerary of Travel and CTC are properly filled out including the signatures of the signatories indicated therein;


instruct the HRMO, the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to see to it that payrolls are supported with duly accomplished DTRs indicating therein the official travel/s, leave/s of absence, work from home of the employee, if any, which must be supported with duly filled out Application for Leave, photo copy of Travel Order, and Accomplishment Report during work from home; 

require the HRMO and the Municipal Accountant to submit the lacking DTRs, Application for Leave, photo copy of Travel Orders and Accomplishment Report of employees who availed WFH as presented in Annexes A,  B and C, respectively;

require the Municipal Treasurer to submit the official receipts of disbursements with total gross and net amounts of P859,955,78 and P817,576.78 respectively, as reflected in Annex D, and that henceforth, she should not make payment for goods without requiring the supplier to issue official receipt or its equivalent;

require the Municipal Accountant and the Supply Officer to submit the PARs of movable non-expendable properties totaling P181,920.00 as presented in Annex E;



require the Municipal Accountant and the Supply Officer to submit the ICS of  semi-expendable items with total cost of P1,065,607.00 as shown in Annex F;



require the Municipal Accountant to submit the list of recipients indicating the exact unit of measure and complete specifications of items distributed totaling P115,875.00 as presented in Annex G;

require the Municipal Accountant that henceforth, always observe the documentary requirements in the disbursement of funds as embodied in COA Circular 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012, thus payment will be made only to claims with complete documentation in order to ascertain the validity, propriety and reliability of the transactions and to avoid suspensions in audit.

We recommended that:

the Sangguniang Bayan consider the immediate revision of the Revenue Code allowing a higher amount of monthly stall rental fee at the public market commensurate to the present purchasing power of the Philippine Peso and the ROI on said property;


the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Treasurer to collect the rental fee of one stall occupied by Lucky 4 Lumber and Hardware since it started operation in January 2007 up to the present in the amount of P84,000.00, including interest and penalties thereon, if warranted;


the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Treasurer to collect immediately the unpaid stall rental fees aggregating P172,000.00 as of December 31, 2020;



the Municipal Mayor through the Municipal Treasurer consider the revision of the Contract of Lease by indicating the rate of monthly rental fee and provision of appropriate interest and/or penalty equivalent to certain percentage of the amount not yet paid and the imposition of higher rental fees for the stalls exceeding a total area of 14 square meters, and

Management strictly enforce the terms and conditions of the Contract of Lease in order to discourage the lessees from being delinquent in paying their obligations.

We recommended that the Management:
Submit justification/s or reason/s for not including the required disclosures and reconciliation in the Notes to Financial Statements noted;
Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to expedite the preparation of the Statement of Comparison Budgets and Actual Amounts;
Direct the Designated Municipal Accountant to:
Submit the required reconciliation and provide disclosures in the Notes to Financial Statements for CY 2021 regarding Reconciliation of Net Cash Flows from Operating Activities; Reconciliation between Actual Amounts on a Comparable Basis as presented in SCABAA and in the Statement of Financial Performance; Amount and Details of the Unexpended Balance of MDRRMF; Total Road Network System; Property, Plant and Equipment; Details on the accounts lumped in the FS. These notes are integral part of the Financial Statements; hence, the Municipal Accountant should ensure that all reconciling items have basis and supported with schedules and necessary details.
Henceforth, strictly comply with the accounting and reporting guidelines for the LDRRMF of LGUs under COA Circular No. 2012-002.

We recommended that the Management:
Require the Sanggunian concerned that authorization for realignments of funds shall be through the passage of an Appropriation Ordinance as prescribed under Sections 321 and 336 of RA 7160, duly submitted to the Sangguniang Panlalawigan for review;
Require the Municipal Planning and Development Officer to ensure that the PPAs to be included in the 20% Development Fund are compliant with the relevant guidelines on the said fund to minimize frequent realignment of funds;
Require the Municipal Budget Officer to maintain Registries to record the changes in the budget;
Require the Municipal Budget Officer and the Municipal Accountant to accomplish the Local Budget Preparation (LBP) Forms as specified in the Budget Operations Manual for LGUs and make sure that no disbursements will be made from realigned funds unless supported with an Appropriation Ordinance; and
Looking forward, coordinate with the Local Finance Committee to improve the budget preparation process to come up with a more comprehensive budget to prioritize and put into action its plans, programs and policies within the constraints of its financial capability as dictated by economic conditions.

12.9	We recommended that Management assign personnel for the constant monitoring and general supervision over each component Barangays to ensure that every barangays act within the scope of their prescribed powers and functions by:
Monitoring their submission of reports to the Municipality complete with the required supporting documentation within the deadline set by the designated municipal accountant and as prescribed by the Manual on Financial Management of Barangays;
Conducting re-orientation seminar focusing on the Appendix C of the  manual which provides for the Matrix of Reports and Forms showing the record/report title, who shall submit or accomplish the report, number of copies to be distributed and to whom it will be distributed, the frequency and due date of submission and the remarks or purpose of the record/report, to know the extent of their duties and responsibilities;
Revisit the personnel complement in the Accounting Unit to ensure timely, complete and accurate preparation and submission of Barangay Financial Statements to the office of the auditor; and
Require explanation/ justification from Barangays who still failed to comply despite constant monitoring and supervision.

We recommended that the Management:
Revisit the personnel complement in the Municipal Treasurer’s Office to ensure continuous operation without affecting operational efficiency in cases where erring AOs will be sanctioned for continuous non-compliance;
Require the Municipal Treasurer to exercise proper management of the funds by:
ensuring accurate and timely reporting and confirm that records in the cashbooks and in the Report of Collections and Deposits are reconciled each month;
ensuring adequate bond for all AOs based on their actual total accountability in pursuance to Treasury Circular No. 02-2009 dated August 6, 2009;
monitoring closely/regularly the activities of all collectors and ensure that all their activities are in accordance with existing rules and regulations; and
requiring all AOs to strictly comply with the prompt deposit of all collections intact to avoid accumulation of cash in their possession;
Require all AOs to explain and justify in cases of failure to follow the existing regulations for collections and deposits;
With close monitoring, strictly impose penalties and sanctions in case of non-compliance thereof especially for those who commits the same violations for three consecutive months by revisiting the existing local issuances and civil service law, rules and regulations; and
